{"title_page": "Washington Square News", "text_new": "{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Washington Square News\n| image = WSNlogo.jpg\n| caption = WSN logo\n| type = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| owners = Independent\n| format = [[Berliner (format)|Berliner]]\n| foundation = 1973\n| headquarters = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| website = [http://nyunews.com nyunews.com]|\n| chiefeditor = Cole Stallone\n| free = https://nyunews.com/tag/archives/\n| sister newspapers = NYU Local\n}}\n'''''Washington Square News''''' is the weekly [[student newspaper]] of [[New York University]] (NYU) and serves the NYU, [[Greenwich Village]], and [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] communities in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. The paper, better known as WSN, has a circulation of 10,000 and an estimated 40,000 readers online. It is published in print on Monday, in addition to online publication Tuesday through Friday during the fall and spring semesters, with additional issues published in the summer.\n\nWSN is run solely by NYU students, with the paper's senior staff mostly composed of [[undergraduates]]. Its offices are located at 75 Third Ave. It serves the student population by helping with opportunities for reporting, writing, editing, coding, photography, video production, design, illustration and business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyunews.com/about/|title=About|website=Washington Square News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThe paper is editorially independent from the university and is solely responsible in selling advertisements to fund its production.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/about/nextgen/cbi_scripts/elizabeth.html|title=Next Generation Radio Project|accessdate=2008-10-03|publisher=NPR|year=2004\u201311|author=Elizabeth Castro|work=2004 National College Media Convention}}</ref>\n\nThe term for the positions of [[editor-in-chief]] and managing editor is one calendar year, beginning in the spring semester and ending after the fall semester. \n\n== History ==\nThe newspaper was born in 1973 as the result of NYU's merging of their two campus weeklies: the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] campus in the [[Bronx]] had published ''The Heights Daily News,'' while the [[Washington Square Park|Washington Square]] campus in [[Lower Manhattan]] originally published ''The Washington Square Journal.''\n\nIn 2000, WSN launched its website [http://nyunews.com nyunews.com]. In 2017, WSN launched its podcast, \"Newsflash,\" and then rebranded the following year as \"Washington Square Noise.\" In 2018, WSN launched its digital weekly magazine \"Under the Arch.\"\n\n== Awards ==\n\nIn 2009, reporters Marc Beja and Adam Playford (Editor-in-Chief, 2008) won 1st place in the category of \"Best News Story\" from the New York State Press Association and National Winner in the category of \"In-depth reporting\" from the Society of Professional Journalists. At the same time Alvin Chang (Editor-in-Chief, 2007) won best columnist.\n\nWashington Square News won an [[Associated Collegiate Press]] [[National Pacemaker Awards|Pacemaker award]] in 2004, that same year it was awarded the title of ''Overall Best Newspaper.'' It won the Pacemaker Award again in 2019.<ref name=\"thev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thevillager.com/villager_50/washingtonsquarenews.html|title=Washington Square News Voted Best Undergraduate Paper|accessdate=2008-10-03|date=2004-03-14|work=The Villager}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the paper won seven first-place awards in the Division 1 \"Better College Newspaper Contest\" of the New York State Press Association.\n\n== Notable former staff ==\n\n*[[Shaun Assael]], author, staff writer at ESPN The Magazine\n*[[William Bastone|Bill Bastone]], editor, [[The Smoking Gun]]\n*Cindy Behrman, advertising editor, Suddler & Hennesey; writer, Village Voice and New York Press (deceased July 22, 2008)\n*[[Marc Bell (entrepreneur)|Marc H. Bell]], CEO of Penthouse Media Group\n*Russell Berman, reporter, ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''\n*Matt Buchanan, executive editor, [[Vox Media|Eater]]\n*Alvin Chang, senior reporter, [[Vox Media|Vox]]\n*Fred Clarke, Democratic Party communications strategist; IBM communications manager\n*[[Katherine Creag]], television reporter, [[Good Day New York]]\n*[http://muckrack.com/charles-dharapak Charles Dharapak], photojournalist\n* [[Jill Filipovic]], author and writer at Feministe\n*Bradley Hope, reporter, [[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]\n*Eileen \"E.P.\" Gunn, 'Eco-Nomics' columnist, [[TheStreet.com]], freelance writer/editor/lecturer\n*Gary He, freelance photojournalist\n*Annette Heist, senior producer, [[Gimlet Media]]\n*Tim Herrera, founding editor, [[The New York Times|NYTimes]]' Smarter Living\n*Eric Kohn, senior editor and chief film critic, [[Indiewire]]\n*Jessica Letkemann, former editor, [[billboard.com]]\n*Mark Mueller, former staff writer, [[Newark Star-Ledger]] (shares 2005 [[Pulitzer Prize]])\n*Jon Mummolo, [[Princeton University]] politics professor\n*Lindsay Noonan, Writer/Producer at [[CNN]]\n*Andrew Nusca, editor, [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]\n*Amy Odell, author and former editor, [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]\n*Brian O'Keefe, deputy editor, [[Fortune Magazine]]\n*[[Kira Peikoff]], author, [http://www.kirapeikoff.com/ The Unholy Grail]\n*Adam Playford, investigations editor, [[Tampa Bay Times]]\n*David E. Rovella, managing editor at [[Bloomberg News]], Attorney\n*[[Joel Sherman (sportswriter)|Joel Sherman]], sportswriter/columnist, New York Post\n*Rachel Holliday Smith, reporter, [[THE CITY (website)|The City]]\n*[[Gene Weingarten]], Washington Post columnist; 2008, 2010 Pulitzer Prize winner\n*Scott Wenger, former assistant managing editor, [[Daily News (New York)]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Greenwich Village]]\n*[[List of New York City newspapers and magazines]]\n*[[New York University]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://nyunews.com Washington Square News]\n*[http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/archives/rg_39_178/ Washington Square News] at New York University Archives at New York University Special Collections\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York University]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1973]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Washington Square News\n| image = WSNlogo.jpg\n| caption = WSN logo\n| type = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| owners = Independent\n| format = [[Berliner (format)|Berliner]]\n| foundation = 1973\n| headquarters = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| website = [http://nyunews.com nyunews.com]\n|}}\n'''''Washington Square News''''' is the weekly [[student newspaper]] of [[New York University]] (NYU) and serves the NYU, [[Greenwich Village]], and [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] communities in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. The paper, better known as WSN, has a circulation of 10,000 and an estimated 40,000 readers online. It is published in print on Monday, in addition to online publication Tuesday through Friday during the fall and spring semesters, with additional issues published in the summer.\n\nWSN is run solely by NYU students, with the paper's senior staff mostly composed of [[undergraduates]]. Its offices are located at 75 Third Ave.\n\nThe paper is editorially independent from the university and is solely responsible in selling advertisements to fund its production.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/about/nextgen/cbi_scripts/elizabeth.html|title=Next Generation Radio Project|accessdate=2008-10-03|publisher=NPR|year=2004\u201311|author=Elizabeth Castro|work=2004 National College Media Convention}}</ref>\n\nThe term for the positions of [[editor-in-chief]] and managing editor is one calendar year, beginning in the spring semester and ending after the fall semester.\n\n== History ==\nThe newspaper was born in 1973 as the result of NYU's merging of their two campus weeklies: the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] campus in the [[Bronx]] had published ''The Heights Daily News,'' while the [[Washington Square Park|Washington Square]] campus in [[Lower Manhattan]] originally published ''The Washington Square Journal.''\n\nIn 2000, WSN launched its website [http://nyunews.com nyunews.com]. In 2017, WSN launched its podcast, \"Newsflash,\" and then rebranded the following year as \"Washington Square Noise.\" In 2018, WSN launched its digital weekly magazine \"Under the Arch.\"\n\n== Awards ==\n\nIn 2009, reporters Marc Beja and Adam Playford (Editor-in-Chief, 2008) won 1st place in the category of \"Best News Story\" from the New York State Press Association and National Winner in the category of \"In-depth reporting\" from the Society of Professional Journalists. At the same time Alvin Chang (Editor-in-Chief, 2007) won best columnist.\n\nWashington Square News won an [[Associated Collegiate Press]] [[National Pacemaker Awards|Pacemaker award]] in 2004, that same year it was awarded the title of ''Overall Best Newspaper.'' It won the Pacemaker Award again in 2019.<ref name=\"thev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thevillager.com/villager_50/washingtonsquarenews.html|title=Washington Square News Voted Best Undergraduate Paper|accessdate=2008-10-03|date=2004-03-14|work=The Villager}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the paper won seven first-place awards in the Division 1 \"Better College Newspaper Contest\" of the New York State Press Association.\n\n== Notable former staff ==\n\n*[[Shaun Assael]], author, staff writer at ESPN The Magazine\n*[[William Bastone|Bill Bastone]], editor, [[The Smoking Gun]]\n*Cindy Behrman, advertising editor, Suddler & Hennesey; writer, Village Voice and New York Press (deceased July 22, 2008)\n*[[Marc Bell (entrepreneur)|Marc H. Bell]], CEO of Penthouse Media Group\n*Russell Berman, reporter, ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''\n*Matt Buchanan, executive editor, [[Vox Media|Eater]]\n*Alvin Chang, senior reporter, [[Vox Media|Vox]]\n*Fred Clarke, Democratic Party communications strategist; IBM communications manager\n*[[Katherine Creag]], television reporter, [[Good Day New York]]\n*[http://muckrack.com/charles-dharapak Charles Dharapak], photojournalist\n* [[Jill Filipovic]], author and writer at Feministe\n*Bradley Hope, reporter, [[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]\n*Eileen \"E.P.\" Gunn, 'Eco-Nomics' columnist, [[TheStreet.com]], freelance writer/editor/lecturer\n*Gary He, freelance photojournalist\n*Annette Heist, senior producer, [[Gimlet Media]]\n*Tim Herrera, founding editor, [[The New York Times|NYTimes]]' Smarter Living\n*Eric Kohn, senior editor and chief film critic, [[Indiewire]]\n*Jessica Letkemann, former editor, [[billboard.com]]\n*Mark Mueller, former staff writer, [[Newark Star-Ledger]] (shares 2005 [[Pulitzer Prize]])\n*Jon Mummolo, [[Princeton University]] politics professor\n*Lindsay Noonan, Writer/Producer at [[CNN]]\n*Andrew Nusca, editor, [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]\n*Amy Odell, author and former editor, [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]\n*Brian O'Keefe, deputy editor, [[Fortune Magazine]]\n*[[Kira Peikoff]], author, [http://www.kirapeikoff.com/ The Unholy Grail]\n*Adam Playford, investigations editor, [[Tampa Bay Times]]\n*David E. Rovella, managing editor at [[Bloomberg News]], Attorney\n*[[Joel Sherman (sportswriter)|Joel Sherman]], sportswriter/columnist, New York Post\n*Rachel Holliday Smith, reporter, [[THE CITY (website)|The City]]\n*[[Gene Weingarten]], Washington Post columnist; 2008, 2010 Pulitzer Prize winner\n*Scott Wenger, former assistant managing editor, [[Daily News (New York)]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Greenwich Village]]\n*[[List of New York City newspapers and magazines]]\n*[[New York University]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://nyunews.com Washington Square News]\n*[http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/archives/rg_39_178/ Washington Square News] at New York University Archives at New York University Special Collections\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York University]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1973]]\n", "name_user": "Andrewmoody71", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_Square_News"}
{"title_page": "Sally Gimson", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2014}}\n{{third-party|date=May 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Councillor|Cllr]]\n| name        = Sally Gimson\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| office1     = [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Borough Councillor]]<br>for [[Highgate (Camden ward)|Highgate ward]]\n| term_start1 = 15 September 2011\n| term_end1   = 2014\n| predecessor1 =  Michael Nicolaides\n| successor1  =\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = \n| residence   = \n| nationality = British\n| education   = \n| party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| religion    = \n| spouse      = [[Andrew Gimson]]\n| children    = 3\n| relatives   = \n| signature   = \n| website     = [http://sallygimson.co.uk/ sallygimson.co.uk]\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n\n'''Sally Gimson''' (n\u00e9e Malcolm-Smith)<ref>Boris: The Adventures of Boris Johnson, Andrew Gimson, Simon & Schuster, 2006</ref>  is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]], ex-councillor in the [[Highgate|Highgate ward]] of [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Council]].<ref>[http://democracy.camden.gov.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=1124/ Sally Gimson - Camden Council website]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://camdenlabour.org.uk/your-representatives/highgate/ Sally Gimson - Camden Labour Party website]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGimson graduated from the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1987 with a degree in Modern Languages, before training as a journalist.<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/sally-gimson-73a47123/?originalSubdomain=uk</ref>\n\nUntil her election to Camden Council she was Head of Public Policy at [[Victim Support]], and she was previously Director of Communications at the [[Family and Parenting Institute]].<ref>http://www.battleofideas.org.uk/2012/speaker_detail/6182/</ref>\n\nSally Gimson was an unsuccessful [[parliamentary candidate]] in the [[South Leicestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Leicestershire constituency]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]]. She served in the council cabinet as the chief of adult health and social care until she challenged Council leader [[Sarah Hayward]] losing by 24 votes to 15, subsequently returning to the backbenches.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rachel Roberts |url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/camden-council-leader-sarah-hayward-sees-off-challenge-from-within-1-4520817 |title=Camden Council leader Sarah Hayward sees off challenge from within - Politics - Hampstead Highgate Express |publisher=Hamhigh.co.uk |date= |accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> On October 27th 2019 Gimson was selected by Bassetlaw Constituency Labour Party to be their prospective parliamentary candidate for the next general election<ref>{{cite web|author=Sienna Rodgers |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/10/super-sunday-labour-candidate-selection-results/ |title=Super Sunday: Labour candidate selection results|publisher=LabourList |date=27 October 2019 |accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>, although she did not end up contesting that position in December 2019 due to a veto by the Labour [[National Executive Committee|NEC]].\n\n==Personal life==\nSally is married to political [[journalist]] [[Andrew Gimson]], with whom she has three children. She has previously written about hers and her husband's opposing political positions.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/dec/17/tory-labour-married-couples/ Tory and Labour: Our very own coalition, Guardian, 17 December 2011]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sallygimson.co.uk/ Official Sally Gimson website]\n*[http://labourlist.org/author/sally-gimson/ Articles by Sally Gimson on Labour List]\n*[http://www.newstatesman.com/writers/sally__gimson Articles by Sally Gimson on the New Statesman]\n*[http://democracy.camden.gov.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=1124 democracy.camden.gov.uk]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gimson, Sally}}\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Camden]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n\n\n{{UK-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2014}}\n{{third-party|date=May 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Councillor|Cllr]]\n| name        = Sally Gimson\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| office1     = [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Borough Councillor]]<br>for [[Highgate (Camden ward)|Highgate ward]]\n| term_start1 = 15 September 2011\n| term_end1   = 2014\n| predecessor1 =  Michael Nicolaides\n| successor1  =\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = \n| residence   = \n| nationality = British\n| education   = \n| party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| religion    = \n| spouse      = [[Andrew Gimson]]\n| children    = 3\n| relatives   = \n| signature   = \n| website     = [http://sallygimson.co.uk/ sallygimson.co.uk]\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n\n'''Sally Gimson''' (n\u00e9e Malcolm-Smith)<ref>Boris: The Adventures of Boris Johnson, Andrew Gimson, Simon & Schuster, 2006</ref>  is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]], ex-councillor in the [[Highgate|Highgate ward]] of [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Council]].<ref>[http://democracy.camden.gov.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=1124/ Sally Gimson - Camden Council website]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://camdenlabour.org.uk/your-representatives/highgate/ Sally Gimson - Camden Labour Party website]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGimson graduated from the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1987 with a degree in Modern Languages, before training as a journalist.<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/sally-gimson-73a47123/?originalSubdomain=uk</ref>\n\nUntil her election to Camden Council she was Head of Public Policy at [[Victim Support]], and she was previously Director of Communications at the [[Family and Parenting Institute]].<ref>http://www.battleofideas.org.uk/2012/speaker_detail/6182/</ref>\n\nSally Gimson was an unsuccessful [[parliamentary candidate]] in the [[South Leicestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Leicestershire constituency]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]]. She served in the council cabinet as the chief of adult health and social care until she challenged Council leader [[Sarah Hayward]] losing by 24 votes to 15, subsequently returning to the backbenches.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rachel Roberts |url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/camden-council-leader-sarah-hayward-sees-off-challenge-from-within-1-4520817 |title=Camden Council leader Sarah Hayward sees off challenge from within - Politics - Hampstead Highgate Express |publisher=Hamhigh.co.uk |date= |accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> On October 27th 2019 Gimson was selected by Bassetlaw Constituency Labour Party to be their prospective parliamentary candidate for the next general election<ref>{{cite web|author=Sienna Rodgers |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/10/super-sunday-labour-candidate-selection-results/ |title=Super Sunday: Labour candidate selection results|publisher=LabourList |date=27 October 2019 |accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>, although she did not end up constesting that position in December 2019 due to a veto by the Labour [[National Executive Committee|NEC]].\n\n==Personal life==\nSally is married to political [[journalist]] [[Andrew Gimson]], with whom she has three children. She has previously written about hers and her husband's opposing political positions.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/dec/17/tory-labour-married-couples/ Tory and Labour: Our very own coalition, Guardian, 17 December 2011]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n<references 