rtment at the University of Budapest. There he taught Greek and modern Greek literature. He also worked on the translation and anthology of a wealth of texts in the Hungarian language. Through this work, Hatzis established Greek Studies in Hungary and contributed to the spread of Greek culture.\n\nFamous works of Hatzis include:\n*''\u03a4\u03bf \u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03ae\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2'' (The end of our small town), 1960.\n*''\u0391\u03bd\u03c5\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03ac\u03c3\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9'' (Defenceless), 1966.\n*''\u03a4\u03bf \u0394\u03b9\u03c0\u03bb\u03cc \u0392\u03b9\u03b2\u03bb\u03af\u03bf'' (The double book), 1976, considered as one of the most important novels in post-war Greek literature.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Onassis Cultural Centre: |url=http://www.athenspotlighted.gr/media/onassis_cultural_centre_2011_2012.pdf |work=athenspotlighted |accessdate=14 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407061121/http://www.athenspotlighted.gr/media/onassis_cultural_centre_2011_2012.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2014 }}</ref>\n*''\u03a3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03ad\u03c2'' (Studies), 1976.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hatzis, Dimitrios}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ioannina]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Greece politicians]]\n[[Category:Greek journalists]]\n[[Category:Greek male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Greek novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Greek poets]]\n[[Category:Zosimaia school alumni]]\n[[Category:National Liberation Front (Greece) members]]\n[[Category:Democratic Army of Greece personnel]]\n[[Category:Exiles of the Greek Civil War]]\n[[Category:Greek prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriates in Hungary]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "